<section id="links">

  <header>
    <h2>Links</h2>
  </header>

  <p><strong>Linked tags</strong> turn chips into navigation or filter controls while keeping their inline footprint. Use them for category filters, related content, or contextual shortcuts where a standard link feels too small and a button would be too heavy.</p>

	<div class="section-example">
		<h1 style="margin: 0">
			<a class="tag">Regular</a> 
			<a class="tag red">Red</a> 
			<a class="tag yellow">Yellow</a> 
			<a class="tag blue">Blue</a> 
			<a class="tag green">Green</a> 
			<a class="tag purple">Purple</a> 
			<a class="tag orange">Orange</a>
		</h1>
	</div>

  <p class="note"><strong>Interaction:</strong> ensure linked tags keep the standard focus ring, provide enough padding for touch targets, and avoid relying solely on color to communicate purpose—combine hue with copy or an icon.</p>

  <div class="code-example">
    
    <pre><code class="html">&lt;a class="tag"&gt;...&lt;/a&gt;</code></pre>
  
  </div>


</section>

